From physical coordinates to pixel coordinates
For a point \(P = [W,H,D]\) within our FOV, the pixel coordinates \(w,h\) will be the vector \(K P\), normalized by \(D\): \[
K P =
K = \begin{bmatrix}
f_x & 0 & c_x \\
0 & f_y & c_y \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
X \\
Y \\
D
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
f_x W + c_x D \\
f_y H + c_y D \\
D
\end{bmatrix}
\]
So that pixel coordinates are \(w = f_x\frac{W}{D} + c_x\) and \(h = f_y\frac{H}{D} + c_y\)
